      "desc": "The narrow lanes surrounding Nakamise Shopping Street and Senso-ji are packed with vendors selling some of Tokyo's most iconic and social-media-famous street snacks. Look for freshly grilled ningyo-yaki (fish- and bell-shaped red bean cakes), thick rolled tamagoyaki (sweet egg omelette on a stick), melon pan straight from the oven, strawberry daifuku, and crispy senbei rice crackers made to order. The crowds and aromas are part of the experience — arrive hungry and graze your way toward the temple.\n\n- Ningyo-yaki — red bean cakes molded into charming Asakusa-themed shapes, grilled fresh in iron molds\n- Tamagoyaki — thick sweet rolled egg omelette on a stick, a Tsukiji and Asakusa staple\n- Melon pan — soft, sweet bread with a crispy sugar crust, best eaten warm right from the bakery\n- Strawberry daifuku — mochi filled with fresh whole strawberry and sweet cream\n- Agemanju — deep-fried steamed buns with sweet red bean filling, crispy outside and pillowy inside\n- Senbei — freshly grilled rice crackers made to order, brushed with soy sauce over an open flame",
      "url": "",
      "cat": "Food & Drink",
      "lat": 35.714,
      "lng": 139.7965
